<HEAD>Eds: Forrest and Lissa are cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of calls to the police and fire departments' 911 emergency number went unanswered Saturday because of a technical problem that knocked out the system for more than four hours. Authorities said they plan to investigate whether the outage, the first in the 911 system's five years of operation, resulted in injury, death or fire damage that could have been avoided had the system been working properly. `` At this point we just do n't know,'' said police Capt. <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewallen </PERSON>. `` I can say that this is a very serious problem. It is something that quite obviously we'll have to find remedies to ensure that it never happens again.'' The problems began at 1 p.m. when equipment that allows the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to transfer calls to the <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> stopped working, said <PERSON> Lissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Zanville </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the system. The equipment failure created a backlog that allowed only one in five calls to reach a 911 operator at the central communications center in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where all 911 calls within city limits are directed, she said. From 3 to 3:40 p.m., the system went down entirely and no calls got through. By 5:14 p.m., <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> technicians had the system working again, Ms. <PERSON> Zanville </PERSON> said. The number of calls that went unanswered was unknown, but the system normally handles 5,000 to 7,000 calls a day, and a four-hour breakdown would easily have left hundreds of calls unanswered, said <PERSON> Lewallen </PERSON>. Not all of those unanswered calls would be emergencies. <PERSON> Lewallen </PERSON> said that about 75 percent of the 4 million calls dialed eac