<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Saturday released 20 Iranians imprisoned for political crimes, extending an olive branch to the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> government. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> rebuffed the move and most of the freed prisoners claimed they had been beaten and tortured by the Afghans. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said the prisoners were released to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the revolution in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that brought <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> to power. `` They be being released as goodwill gesture toward the Iranian government,'' <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> told a news conference. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s highest-raking diplomat in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, Charge d'Affairs <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Intizari </PERSON>, welcomed the release but said it would not help improve relations between <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> supports the efforts of the Moslem guerrillas, or mujahedeen, fighting to overthrow the government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, who has been supported by Soviet troops since December 1979. Soviet forces are in the final days of a withdrawal to be completed by Wednesday under a U.N.-sponsored agreement. `` We have not recognized this government for the past 10 years. How can it improve relations?'' <PERSON> Intizari </PERSON> asked shortly before he greeted the former prisoners at a hotel in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. `` We are waiting for a government with the mujahedeen,'' he said. The 20 men had been imprisoned for 2 to 10 years after they were tried and convicted of various political crimes, including aiding the Moslem rebels. All appeared to be in good health, although many showed reporters scars they said were caused by cigarette brns, missing teeth, and said they had were repeatedly beaten and tortured. The Afghan government had no immediate comment on the allegations. Seventeen of the men were to be flown to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> on Sunday, <PERSON> Intizari </PERSON> said. One man claimd he was Afghan and will stay in the country. The other two said they did not want to go back to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and were released to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>.
