<HEAD>North Accuses South of Shooting Across Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on Sunday accused South Korean troops of firing across the border at its policemen. The North's official <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the firing `` gravely threatened the safety of the civilian policemen of our side on routine duty at the post.'' It did not mention any injuries or damage. `` It was entirely due to the patience and self-control of the civilian policemen of our side that this incident did not expand into an arms conflict between the two sides,'' said the agency, monitored in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. It said several <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> soldiers fired `` many bullets'' from automatic rifles Sunday afternoon from the Chosan military police post in the Demilitarized Zone that divides the two Koreas. The post is west of <LOCATION> Munsan </LOCATION>, a city about 25 miles north of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and about 10 miles south of the truce village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> in the DMZ. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imperialists and the South Korean puppets are committing one military provocation after another on the ground and in the sea while staging the adventurous ` Team Spirit 89' joint military maneuvers,'' the report said. `` This clearly shows how desperately they are making new war provocation moves to invade the northern half of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, bringing the situation of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula to the extreme pitch of strain,'' it said. Team Spirit is an annual U.S.-South Korean joint military exercise, described as purely defensive. The North, however, says it is a rehearsal for invasion and has demanded it be canceled to improve the atmosphere for North-South talks. The two sides have held a number of contacts in recent months aimed at easing tensions and e