<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prospect of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> shaking hands at their upcoming summit is causing surprisingly little anxiety in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Several years ago, reports of high-level chumminess between the two communist giants would have caused sleepless nights among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, wary of a renewed military and political pact between the powerful neighbors. But Asian and Soviet experts in and out of government say the relaxation of tensions between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, while not totally to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s advantage, could produce some positive steps in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> region. `` Whatever concerns we might have had four years ago, had this come suddenly, have now been gradually reduced,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreisberg </PERSON>, a specialist in <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> matters with the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>. `` No one now expects the Soviets and the Chinese to restart the security alliance they had in the 1950s,'' <PERSON> Kreisberg </PERSON> said, pointing to comments from <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> that his moves toward easing tensions with the Soviets are not designed to damage U.S.-Chinese relations. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is to travel to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in May for the summit with <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, marking the first top-level meetings between the two countries since <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Zedong </PERSON> in 1959. The sessions are designed to formally end the 30 years of hostility between the one-time rivals for leadership of the communist world and `` achieve a complete normalization of relations,'' Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> announced last week. `` There may be some Americans who are anxious about this,'' said <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Kallgren </PERSON>, a director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Kallgren </PERSON> points to the rapid growth of the economic relationship between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, arguing that there is little reason for the Chinese to disturb that trend. And the Sino-Soviet relationship `` has a long way to go'' to match it, she said. `` Are we beginning to see the kind of close -LRB- Chinese-Soviet -RRB- relationship that we saw 30 years ago? It seems to me that there are a lot of reasons why that analogy is a very limited value,'' she said. `` There has n't been much of a wringing of hands,'' agreed a senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official who follows <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> affairs. `` We've had a chance to get used to this idea ... It's been coming for years.'' The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name, said the Soviet move to mend the ties that had been cut in 1960 began under former Soviet leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. The Chinese felt threatened by the Soviet-backed Vietnamese invasion of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and the Soviet intrusion into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, and t