<HEAD>Afghans Prepare to Defend Link to Outside World</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the last Soviet troops prepare to leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, a key question remains: Can the Afghan air force keep open <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s airport, the capital's vital link to the outside world? Col. <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinokunov </PERSON>, commander of a small Soviet guard detachment at the airport, has no doubts. `` The Afghan pilots have been trained in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and have continued to study here with us,'' said <PERSON> Vinokunov </PERSON>, who has been in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> more than two years. `` They'll be able to handle it, no worse than we did.'' His words should be put to the test this week, sometime before Wednesday, the deadine for the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> to be out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, a city of about 2 million, is surrounded by high mountain passes, which are relatively easy for the U.S.-backed rebels to block to cut the flow of goods to the capital. Winter snow and avalanches add to the problem of bringing in supplies. With no obvious end in sight to the 10-year-old civil war, the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport will be the key link to the rest of the world. The rebels are armed with sophisticated, heat-seeking missiles. The airport has not come under a rebel rocket attack in more than a month, and no airliner has been shot down over <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. But the threat has scared off all civilian aircraft except <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ariana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> and an occasional <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plane On Sunday, though, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> program to bring emergency supplies to the capital was interrupted when an <ORGANIZATION> Ethiopian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet carrying the goods was ordered by t