<HEAD>The Honeymoon's Over In Divided Indiana House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three months after Republicans and Democrats in the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> found themselves deadlocked at 50 members each and pledged to cooperate, their marriage of convenience is showing signs of strain. `` The honeymoon appears to be over, and the in-laws have moved in,'' is how House Republican Speaker <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON> put it recently. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> became bogged down in a series of disputes after Democrats began to exert their new power to block a 51-vote majority and Republicans showed frustration at losing control of the chamber for the first time in 12 years. `` It was strained, and there were times I think people were frustrated,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democratic floor leader. Both sides in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> pledged unprecedented bipartisan cooperation after Democrats picked up two seats in the November election, which also made <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> the state's first Democratic governor in 20 years, and the 100 seats split 50-50. After a deadlock on organization day in late November, negotiations finished on Thanksgiving yielded a unique power-sharing agreement. It called for co-speakers, one from each party presiding on alternate days; co-chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s 28 committees; and new rules designed to prevent one party from holding the other party's legislation hostage It seemed to work after the session opened Jan. 4, but events in the last couple of weeks demonstrated one party can still impose its will on the other. On a day when Democratic Speaker <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> was presiding, Democrats prevented a committee report on a Republican bill from moving to the amendment stage on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. Two days later, Democrats voted as a block to prevent a majority and defeat 40 Republican-written amendments to a bill to create a state lottery. `` I think obviously we've been shown that 50 united people can deny 50 other people the opportunity to have input,'' said <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON>. `` It's easy to take 50 votes and stop something. It's not so easy to get 51 votes and enact something,'' he said. During the debate on the committee report, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republican Floor Leader <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellinger </PERSON> argued that Democrats were stepping back from a tie-vote rule they had insisted upon during November's negotiations That rule allows a bill to emerge from committee on a tie vote. Previously, a bill had to have a majority vote to advance. <PERSON> Dellinger </PERSON> said blocking a committee report `` was like having a red flag in front of a bull.'' So, a few days later the lottery bill, which had been expected to enjoy broad bipartisan support, triggered a partisan debate. Republicans offered a series of amendments proposing expenditures for education and human services programs that Democrats have long favored. That forced the Democrats to vote against the amendments in order to preserve the lottery bill as <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> wanted it. After that, <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON> said, `` There was some frustration that partisanship on the part of the Democrats was spoiling what had been a fairly even-handed system so far.'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> responded that Democrats presided fairly, adding: `` There's no question there's frustration -LRB- among the GOP -RRB- There's the same frustration I felt as a minority member of this body.'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said he hopes Republicans would `` not get involved in tit for tat. That serves no one, Republicans or Democrats.'' <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON> said he hopes the displays of power `` will bring seasoned minds to think there has to be a better way.'' Other leaders were not so sure. `` It appears to me we are headed for a long, strange year or two years,'' until another election gives one party a majority, said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON>.
