<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prospect that <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> may soon die presents his successor, <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, with the unpalatable decision of whether to let him return home. It also has led to speculation about who will lead <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' followers upon his death The former president has been hospitalized in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> since Jan. 16 and last week suffered a relapse of pneumonia and bronchial asthma. He remains in critical condition on a respirator in an intensive care unit. Supporters of the 71-year-old <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> say he is dying and wants to return to the country he ruled for 20 years until he was ousted in 1986 in a popular uprising. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has repeatedly banned <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> from returning, citing security concerns, but she allowed a Filipino official to travel to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to talk with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> representatives. The decision suggested she might consider negotiating a deal, possibly involving the return of some of the estimated $ 10 billion <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his associates allegedly embezzled during his administration. Because the government's position is not entirely clear, rumors abound about an impending deal. There is lively debate among politicians and commentators on what Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> should do. `` National interest demands that we deny him a homecoming,'' wrote the independent Philippine Daily Inquirer. `` In sum ... <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, even in death, should not be allowed to return to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.'' But Senate President <PERSON> Jovito </PERSON> <PERSON> Salonga </PERSON> said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> should be allowed to come home to die if he can settle federal racketeering charges <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities filed against him in October. Even if <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> dies abroad, the government would face the emotional question of whether to allow him to be buried in his native land. The administration has given mixed signals on the issue, and opinion among politicians and commentators is divided. Last week, several <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> newspapers quoted officials as saying the Cabinet has opted for a `` Napoleonic solution'': banning <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' body from being returned to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> The phrase was coined by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Osmena </PERSON>, who recommended the government follow the example of <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>. The French emperor died in exile on <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION> island in 1821, and his body was not returned to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> until 19 years later. <PERSON> Osmena </PERSON> said the government would face mass demonstrations by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' followers and left-wing extremists if <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' body were brought to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> says the matter has not been settled. Forbidding a funeral here would infuriate <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters and risk portraying Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> as vengeful and unforgiving, especially since she refused <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' requests to return home in May after his 95-year-old mother died. `` Considering the fact that we Filipinos revere the dead and even forgive their misdeeds and wrongdoings while alive, a <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> burial in his hometown should make <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> rise above the pettiness and recriminations of the people around her,'' wrote independent columnist <PERSON> Emil </PERSON> <PERSON> Jurado </PERSON> in The <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> Standard. On Friday, Filipino news organizations received anonymous letters that said a coup called `` Operation Valentine'' would be staged around Valentine's Day, Wednesday. Military officers alleged to be part of the conspiracy included some of Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s most trusted lieutenants. It appeared the letters were a right-wing attempt to sow distrust and to pressure Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> into acceding to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' demand to return home. She dismissed the letters as a prank. But military Chief of Staff Gen. <PERSON> Renato </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> said three renegade officers, including former Lt. Col. <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> `` Gringo'' <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>, met recently in secret to discuss joining forces. <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> led an August 1987 coup attempt in which 53 people were killed and hundreds wounded. Another question raised by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' poor health is who would lead his supporters should he die. Several candidates have emerged, including Vice President <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION>, who met <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> this month, and Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>, whom Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> fired as defense minister in 1986 after a failed coup by his followers. Several politicians have pointed to <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cojuangco </PERSON>, a wealthy former <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> ally who lives in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cojuangco </PERSON> is also a cousin of Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. `` The figure to watch is really <PERSON> Danding </PERSON>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bonifacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillego </PERSON>, calling <PERSON> Cojuangco </PERSON> by his nickname. `` People admire him because he did not bring his wealth out of the country and knows how to take care of his people.'' Former Labor Minister <PERSON> Blas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ople </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Cojuangco </PERSON> `` will be a serious competitor within the opposition for use of assets if he has a mind to use them.''
</TEXT>
