<HEAD>Few Withdrawing Money from S&amp;Ls, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly all Americans are aware of the crisis in the nation's savings and loan industry but only a small fraction are withdrawing their money, according to a poll released Sunday by <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. The telephone poll of 509 adults, conducted Feb. 8-9, found that 84 percent were aware of the crisis and that 49 percent had savings accounts in S & amp; L institutions. Of those with <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L accounts, it said, 6 percent were planning to withdraw their money because of the crisis, and 4 percent had withdrawn money from an S & amp; L within the last few months. Thirty-nine percent of those polled predicted they would be affected eventually by the problems besetting savings and loan institutions. A majority, 56 percent, said they approved in general of a plan by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to bail out the S & amp; Ls by selling bonds to supplement the federal insurance program that guarantees deposits in the instititions. Thirty-seven percent said they did not like <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan The survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percent, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> said in a release.
