<HEAD>Relatives Weep At Church Service For Jailed Hunger Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ELIZABETH, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Relatives of black prisoners staging a hunger strike prayed and wept Sunday at a church service held to support the strikers' demands for freedom. The service took place at Anglican church in the black township of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION> a day after the government banned all public gatherings intended to show solidarity with the detainees. The service proceeded without interruption and there was no sign of security forces. About 300 detainees are involved in the hunger strike, including 105 at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Albans </LOCATION> prison in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION> and about 170 at Diepkloof Prison outside <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. Some of the prisoners have not eaten for 21 days, and lawyers say at least 13 of the Diepkloof hunger strikers have been hospitalized. Many of the detainees at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Albans </LOCATION> have been held without charge since mid-1986. They include several prominent anti-apartheid leaders who helped organize an effective black consumer boycott in 1985-86. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION>, a township bordering <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>, about 400 people packed into <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stephens </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> for the solidarity service. One of the organizers read a statement from the detainees which said: `` We wish to point out to our parents, wives, children and friends that we will not stop until we are home and free. Any attempt to stop us will fail.'' A civil rights lawyer, M.D. <PERSON> Vabaza </PERSON>, said he visited hunger strikes at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Albans </LOCATION> on Saturday and was told told that two of the detainees had collapsed in their cells, been taken to a hospital for treatment and then returned to the prison. The service was led by black and white clergymen, and