<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Volunteer firemen ran out of water fighting a house fire that killed eight people, and had to refill the water tanks on their trucks five miles away, authorities said. But officials said the fire spread so fast that more water probably would not have saved the lives of the eight family members who died in the blaze early Saturday. `` I do n't think water would have made much of a difference as far as lives,'' said Deputy <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> of the sheriff's office. `` The roof had already caved in when I got there at 3:40 a.m.,'' <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> said. `` It was engulfed in flames. There was n't any sounds coming from inside there then.'' <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON>, who is in his 50s, and his daughter <PERSON> Angela </PERSON>, in her 20s, escaped. His wife, six of their children and a 2-year-old granddaughter were found dead in their beds in two bedrooms _ five in one and three in the other. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> was awakened by the fire and tried to wake his wife, <PERSON> Bernice </PERSON>, `` but she would n't move,'' said <LOCATION> Woodruff </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Creasey </PERSON>. `` He was hysterical,'' the sheriff said. The fire, which authorities believe started from a crack in the chimney attached to a wood-burning stove used to heat the house, was reported by neighbors just after 3 a.m.. <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> said the four 500-gallon trucks from three volunteer fire departments responding to the blaze made five or more trips to fire hydrants in the Grays community, five miles away, to fill up their tanks The home in Revels, about 60 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, was due to be connected to the public water supply in the spring, but was still relying on well water along with other homes in the rural community, according to Woodruff County Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERS