<HEAD>With AM-North Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The special prosecutor for the Iran-Contra affair credits the press with exposing the case and opening it to public scrutiny even if security blocks his case against former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> fails. `` There are two ways of enforcing the law,'' special prosecutor <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> told a group of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> broadcasters Saturday night. `` One is the old way of prosecution, which is long, expensive, cumbersome and sometimes has unforeseeable results. `` And the other way is by exposure and education, and that is what your profession does so well.'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> lawyer, was in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> to be honored by the <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>. The chief justice of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday ordered a delay in the start of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>'s trial to give the full court a chance to consider a dispute over the possible disclosure of national secrets. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> had ordered the trial to begin Monday, but <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorneys asked the high court for the delay based on claims that <PERSON> North </PERSON> could release highly classified documents during his defense. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> praised the media for its coverage of the Iran-Contra affair and the events leading up to the North trial, saying he was surprised how accurate the media reports were about information he later obtained in his own investigation. `` For six months, I got more out of the papers than I did from my entire staff,'' he said. But he said the irony of a strong, effective press is evident in the administration's request to forbid use of certain classified documents by <PERSON> North </PERSON> in his defense. `` The commitment to a public trial leads to the sometimes very difficult choices of whether certain information can be used at trial or whether certain charges must be dropped,'' he said. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, 77, said he believes the trial should continue without further limitations placed on use of evidence, which could lead to the dismissal of some or all charges against <PERSON> North </PERSON> if he is not allowed to use the information to defend himself. `` It's important to see if we can apply the law to all people, all levels of government, and to all activities, whether they are open or secret; and at the same time, preserve our obligation for a public trial,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, was appointed special prosecutor Dec. 19, 1986, by a panel of three federal judges.
