/ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said the hand brakes also should have been set, but were not. But <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Link </ORGANIZATION> officials debate that contention. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>, president of the company, said he does not believe failure to set the hand brakes was a violation of operation procedure. The General Code of Operating Rules, a set of regulations followed by 13 major railroads, including <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Link </ORGANIZATION>, says air brakes `` must not be depended upon to hold a train, engine or car when left unattended.'' <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON> said the phrase `` left unattended'' means when cars that are left for an extended period without supervision, perhaps as long as several days. Over long periods of time, air brakes can lose their holding ability. The hand brakes are used as a backup.
