<HEAD>Yacht Beats 135-year New York-San Francisco Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 10th graf, `Dozens..', with trip completed
in 80 days and 20 hours and other records broken. Picks up 11th graf, `In
a...'. SUBS 14th graf, `The crew...', to give hometowns.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1, FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The yacht Thursday's Child sailed triumphantly under the Golden Gate Bridge on Sunday, breaking by eight days the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-to-San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> speed record set in 1854. The 60-foot sloop crossed the finish line at 12:32 p.m. and was met by cheers and yells from hundreds of spectators. Thursday's Child set sail Nov. 23 on a 14,500-mile voyage that took it around treacherous <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION> on the tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` I would n't do anything different, but I would n't do it again _ once is enough,'' said skipper-owner <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Luhrs </PERSON> after he stepped ashore. <PERSON> Luhrs </PERSON> and the other two crew members waved to the crowd after bettering the 89-day, eight-hour trip by the 229-foot clipper ship Flying Cloud during the Gold Rush. The crew docked the 10-ton vessel at Blossom Rock, about two miles from the Golden Gate, because they said the submerged point is where clipper ships used to drop anchor. About 80 ships were out on <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> to greet the modern racing sloop, while other spectators gathered on the roof of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> and at the south tower of the Golden Gate Bridge. A biplane flew overhead trailing a sign that read: `` We love you TC.'' Thursday's Child's entrance into the bay was delayed for hours by a four-knot outgoing tide and by a lack of wind. The crew tried everything, including putting out a large sail called a spinnaker, but all its sails drooped. Finally, under a bright, cloudless sky the yacht was able to sail under the Golden Gate. Dozens of sailboats and powerboats had headed out the Golden Gate for the occasion and the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> sent a 95-foot cutter and four utility boats to escort the yacht into the bay and lessen the danger of a spectator boat accidentally ramming Thursday's Child. The yacht left from <LOCATION> Sandy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, 18 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and arrived in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> after 80 days and 20 hours, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>, race timekeeper at the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. He said Thursday's Child broke three other sailing records; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to the equator, set in 1856; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION>, 1857; and <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, 1854. The times and old records were not immediately available. In a ship-to-shore interview earlier Sunday, crew member <PERSON> Courtney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazleton </PERSON> said he had `` that coming-home feeling.'' `` It's kind of like a mixed bag of emotions right now,'' said <PERSON> Hazleton </PERSON>. `` Both relief, letdown, that the whole thing's over, and just a general feeling of accomplishment.'' The crew _ <PERSON> Hazleton </PERSON>, 32, of <LOCATION> Palmetto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Luhrs </PERSON>, 44, of <LOCATION> Alachua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Lars </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergstrom </PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>, who helped design the vessel _ had spent Saturday zig-zagging north against a stubborn headwind that delayed the ship's arrival by one day. <PERSON> Luhrs </PERSON> launched Thursday's Child for the 1984 solo trans-Atlantic race, in which she was the first American entry and the first single-hulled boat to finish. The Flying Cloud was a merchantman that also ferried Gold Rush adventurers around the dangerous <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION> at the tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and up to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. It could carry 35 sails on its tall masts and was the fastest of thousands of clippers that raced each other across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. The ship wrecked on rocks off <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, in 1874 and nothing is left of it. In the past seven years, five racing boats trying to beat Flying Cloud's record sank in the howling gales and treacherous rocks of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION>. A second boat also attempting to break Flying Cloud's record was damaged last week in a storm off <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION>. The Bark of the West, a 60-foot monohull, was in its 56th day of sailing. Thursday's Child also had trouble during its run at the record; it had to stop at the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> for repairs after it struck an unknown object. The modern vessel survived <PERSON> Cape </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Hazleton </PERSON> expressed awe and respect for the power of the sea when he recalled the passage around the cape. ` It got pretty bad ... very unpleasant,'' <PERSON> Hazelton </PERSON> said in an interview by radio last week. He said they spent six days and nights sailing into the teeth of wind gusting to 60 knots, through seas that raged from all directions.
