<TEXT>
 Government officials were questioning 22 fishermen Monday who returned to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> after 15 days of captivity in communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The fishermen arrived in the port of <LOCATION> Inchon </LOCATION> aboard two trawlers Sunday and were met by government security officials who declined to be identified. In the past, fishermen captured and released by the north have been questioned several days before being allowed to return to their families. North and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, divided since 1945, are still technically at war and a peace treaty never has been signed. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> seized the fishermen and their two ships on Jan. 28, saying the vessels had illegally entered North Korean territorial waters in the Yellow Sea. On Friday, the president of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sang-hyup </PERSON>, said he had been notified the north would return the fishermen for humanitarian reasons. He said a message from his northern counterpart, <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> <PERSON> Pil </PERSON>, said the decision also was made out of a desire to seek national reconciliation and reunify the two Koreas. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> had claimed that the two boats were captured by a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> navy patrol boat while fishing in international waters. The area where the boats were seized is close to the sea extension of the Korean Military Demarcation Line that separates the two Koreas roughly along the 38th parallel. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCAT