<HEAD>Steel Firms Preparing Trade Cases Against Foreign Rivals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major American steel companies are spending millions of dollars to try to document alleged unfair trading practices by leading steel-exporting nations. The move is part of a campaign by the American steel industry to win an extension of a series of pacts that set product-by-product limits on the amount of foreign steel that can be shipped into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The pacts were negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and other nations in 1984 in response to complaints by American steelmakers that they could not compete with a flood of subsidized, foreign imports. The agreements expire Sept. 30, and <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and other leading steelmakers want to be certain they are renewed. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has pledged to support the pacts, although no specifics have been offered on whether they would be continued in their present form. The wild cards in the negotiations will be the nations themselves. They are under no obligation to restrict their imports again, as they did voluntarily five years ago. In order to pressure the trading partners, American steelmakers have been paying millions of dollars to lawyers to compile `` unfair trading cases'' against the countries, according to <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> executives. In the cases, the lawyers are detailing allegations of foreign government subsidies to steelmakers and `` dumping,'' or selling products in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at below fair-market value. The unfair trading cases may never actually be filed with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, an independent agency with authority to order tariffs or other import relief for injured domestic industries. But the American companies are compiling the cases anyway so the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can use the information as leverage in negotiations. Trade cases are `` an alternative, an expensive undesirable alternative,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Boni </PERSON>, chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said in a recent interview. While steel industry officials are reluctant to publicly discuss the specifics of such cases, <PERSON> Boni </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Parsippany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, spent $ 2 million recently just on lawyers who are compiling them. He said larger steelmakers probably were spending more. Under the five-year trade pacts, imports have been reduced from 26.4 percent of the American steel market in 1984 to about 20.5 percent last year. Meanwhile, employment levels and profit among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steelmakers were up last year over 1987. While <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steelmakers say they continue to need the protection of import curbs, some other American manufacturers contend the restraints have created steel shortages in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and driven up prices.
